{{Infobox book | name = Bill Bryson's African Diary | title_orig = | translator = | image = Doubleday, Bill Bryson, 2002, African Diary book cover.jpg | caption = Cover of 2002 [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] [[hardback]] edition | author = [[Bill Bryson]] | illustrator = Neil Gower | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Kenya]] | genre = [[Travel literature|Travel]] | publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] | pub_date = 2002 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 63 | isbn = 0-7679-1506-2 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = [[Down Under (book)|Down Under]] | followed_by = [[A Short History of Nearly Everything]] }} '''''Bill Bryson's African Diary''''' is a 2002 book by best-selling travel writer [[Bill Bryson]]. The book details a trip Bryson took to [[Kenya]] in 2002. Bryson describes his experiences there and observations about Kenyan culture, geography, and politics, as well as his visits to poverty-fighting projects run by [[CARE (relief)|CARE International]], to which he donated all royalties for the book.<ref>http://www.careinternational.org.uk/news-and-press/press-release-archive-2002/745-bill-bryson-is-this-years-christmas-cracker</ref>
==Reception== In a review published in the Guardian Lionel Shriver was critical of the book's length, describing it as "less a book than a pamphlet". Shriver also disliked the book's tone, "a po-faced, gee-whizz sincerity ill-suited to a writer who has made his reputation for being light and wry (and even snide) in droll travel books."<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/dec/21/billbryson.travel</ref>
{{Bill Bryson}}
