{{Infobox artist | name = Hilda Alexandra Wiseman | image = Photo_of_Hilda_Alexandra_Wiseman.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Hilda Alexandra Wiseman, 1980 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1894|4|7|df=y}} | birth_place = Mooroopna, Victoria, Australia | death_date = {{death date and age|1982|4|28|1894|4|7|df=y}} | death_place = Auckland, New Zealand | nationality = New Zealander | education = Elam School of Art, Seddon Memorial Technical College | field = [[Illustration]], [[Calligraphy]] | training = | movement = linocuts | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = | partner = }}
'''Hilda Alexandra Wiseman''' (1894&ndash;1982) was a notable New Zealand [[bookplate]] designer, artist and calligrapher.
Wiseman was born in [[Mooroopna]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]] on 7 April 1894.<ref name="DNZB Wiseman">{{DNZB|title=Hilda Alexandra Wiseman|first= Georgia|last= Prince|id=4w22|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>
She attended [[Elam School of Art]], and [[Auckland University of Technology|Seddon Memorial Technical College]]<ref name="DNZB Wiseman"/>
Wiseman began her artistic career as a commercial artist at the Chandler and Company advertising firm. In 1925 she created her first [[linocut]] bookplate She went on to design over 100 bookplates.<ref name="DNZB Wiseman"/>
In 1931 she started her own studio, the Selwyn Studio.<ref name="DNZB Wiseman"/>
At the time of her death in 1982 the Auckland Historical Society received her bequest of the Selwyn Studio, and its contents.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Webster|first1=J. P.|title=Hilda Wiseman at Selwyn Studio|url=http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues21to30/wiseman.htm|website=Art New Zealand|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref>
