===Religious sites===

According to one possible explanation, the long barrows served as markers of place that were connected to Early Neolithic ideas about [[cosmology]] and [[spirituality]], and accordingly were centres of ritual activity mediated by the dead.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=43}} The inclusion of human remains has been used to argue that these long barrows were involved in a form of [[ancestor veneration]].{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=43}} Malone suggested that the prominence of these barrows suggested that ancestors were deemed far more important to Early Neolithic people than their Mesolithic forebears.{{sfn|Malone|2001|p=103}} In the early twentieth century, this interpretation of the long barrows as religious sites was often connected to the idea that they were the holy sites of a new religion spread by either settlers or missionaries. This explanation has been less popular with archaeologists since the 1970s.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=42}}

Adopting an approach based in [[cognitive archaeology]], Lewis-Williams and Pearce argued that the chambered long barrows "reflected and at the same time constituted... a culturally specific expression of the neurologically generated tiered cosmos", a cosmos mediated by a system of symbols.{{sfn|Lewis-Williams|Pearce|2005|p=171}} They suggested that the entrances to the chambers were viewed as transitional zones where sacrificial rituals took place, and that they were possibly spaces for the transformation of the dead using fire.{{sfn|Lewis-Williams|Pearce|2005|p=182}}

===Territorial markers===

A second explanation is that these long barrows were intrinsically connected to the transition to farming, representing a new way of looking at the land. In this interpretation, the long barrows served as territorial markers, dividing up the land, signifying that it was occupied and controlled by a particular community, and thus warning away rival groups.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=42}} In defending this interpretation, Malone noted that each "tomb-territory" typically had access to a range of soils and landscape types in its vicinity, suggesting that it could have represented a viable territorial area for a particular community.{{sfn|Malone|2001|p=107}} Also supporting this interpretation is the fact that the distribution of chambered long barrows on some Scottish islands shows patterns that closely mirror modern land divisions between farms and crofts.{{sfn|Malone|2001|p=107}} This interpretation also draws [[ethnography|ethnographic]] parallels from recorded communities around the world, who have also used monuments to demarcate territory.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=43}}

This idea became popular among archaeologists in the 1980s and 1990s, and—in downplaying religion while emphasising an economic explanation for these monuments—it was influenced by [[Marxism|Marxist]] ideas then popular in the European archaeological establishment.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|pp=42, 43}} In the early twenty-first century, archaeologists began to challenge this idea, as evidence emerged that much of Early Neolithic Britain was forested and its inhabitants were likely [[Pastoralism|pastoralist]]s rather than [[agriculturalist]]s. Accordingly, communities in Britain would have been semi-nomadic, with little need for territorial demarcation or clear markings of land ownership.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=43}} Also, this explanation fails to explain why the chambered long barrows should be clustered in certain areas rather than being evenly distributed throughout the landscape.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=43}}

==Later history==

Many of the chambered long barrows have not remained intact, having been damaged and broken up during the millennia.{{sfn|Daniel|1950|p=6}} In some cases, most of the chamber has been removed, leaving only the three-stone dolmen.{{sfn|Daniel|1950|p=7}}

===Antiquarian and archaeological investigation===

The first serious study of chambered long barrows took place in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, when the mounds that covered chambers were removed by agriculture.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=8}}
By the nineteenth century, antiquarians and archaeologists had come to recognise this style of monument as a form of tomb.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=8}} In the latter nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, archaeologists like [[V. Gordon Childe]] held to the [[cultural diffusionism|cultural diffusionist]] view that such Western European monuments had been based on tombs originally produced in parts of the eastern Mediterranean region, suggesting that their ultimate origin was either in Egypt or in Crete.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|pp=8–9}} In this view, the tradition was seen as having spread westward as part of some form of "megalithic religion".{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=9}}

A seminal study of the long barrows authored by the Welsh archaeologist [[Glyn Daniel]] was published in 1958 as ''The Megalith Builders of Western Europe''.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=9}}
In 1950, the archaeologist [[Glyn Daniel]] stated that about a tenth of known chambered long barrows in Britain had been excavated,{{sfn|Daniel|1950|p=3}} while regional field studies helped to list them.{{sfn|Daniel|1950|p=3}}
Few of the earlier excavations recorded or retained any human remains found in the chamber.{{sfn|Malone|2001|p=108}}
From the 1960s onward, archaeological research increasingly focused on examining regional groups of long barrows rather than the wider architectural tradition.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=9}} From this decade onward, the meticulous excavation of various long barrows also led to the widespread recognition that long barrows were often multi-phase monuments which had been changed over time.{{sfn|Lynch|1997|p=9}}

Up until the 1970s, archaeologists widely believed that the long barrows of Western Europe were based on Near Eastern models.{{sfn|Hutton|2013|p=41}}

The archaeologists Lewis-Williams and Pearce opined that the emphasis on classification of these monuments into sub-types could be a self-defeating aim for archaeologists, as it distracted them from the task of explaining the meaning and purpose behind them.{{sfn|Lewis-Williams|Pearce|2005|p=181}}

=== Modern revival ===
{{multiple image
| align = 
| direction = vertical
| width = 
| footer = The Modern Barrows
| image1 = Long_Barrow,_Soulton,_Shropshire.jpg
| alt1 = Construction of the [[Soulton Long Barrow]] in progress in 2018
| caption1 = Construction of the [[Soulton Long Barrow]] in progress in 2018
| image2 = All_cannings_longbarrow_modern_inside.jpg
| alt2 = Inside one of the Chambers of the barrow
| caption2 = Inside one of the Chambers of the barrow
}}
In 2015 the first long barrow in thousands of years, the [[Long Barrow at All Cannings]], inspired by those built in the Neolithic, was built on land just outside the village of [[All Cannings]]. The project was instigated by Tim Daw, a local farmer and steward of [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/11227351/Stonehenge-steward-builds-his-own-burial-chamber.html|title=Stonehenge steward builds his own burial chamber|website=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=2017-08-19}}</ref> The barrow was designed to have a large number of private niches within the stone and earth structure to receive cremation urns.

The structure received significant media attention, with national press writing extensively about the revival of the structures, and various episodes of filming, for example by [[BBC]] ''[[Countryfile]]'' as it was being built. It was fully subscribed within eighteen months.

This was followed soon after by new barrows at: 

* the [[Willow Row Barrow]] at [[St Neots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/local-news/first-burial-barrow-thousands-years-12062456|title=First burial barrow in thousands of years is completed at Hail Weston|first=Julian|last=Makey|date=23 October 2016|website=Cambridge-news.co.uk|accessdate=2017-08-19}}</ref>
* The [[Soulton Long Barrow]] at [[Soulton]] in [[Shropshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-shropshire-38655981/stone-age-burial-mound-could-be-built-in-shropshire|title='Stone age' burial mound could be built in Shropshire|website=BBC News|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>
* Higher Ground Meadow in [[Dorset]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridportnews.co.uk/news/15504547._A_beautiful_place_for_loved_ones_to_rest___New_round_barrow_to_be_built_for_burial_ground/|title='A beautiful place for loved ones to rest': New round barrow to be built for burial ground|website=Bridport and Lyme Regis News|language=en|access-date=2018-04-27}}</ref>

== Examples ==
Notable examples of surviving long barrows include:
* [[West Kennet Long Barrow]], Wiltshire, England
* [[Belas Knap]], Gloucestershire, England
* [[Coldrum Long Barrow]], Kent, England
* [[Uley Long Barrow]], Gloucestershire, England
* [[Stoney Littleton Long Barrow]], Somerset, England
* [[Grønsalen]] on the island of [[Møn]], the largest long barrow in Denmark

