{{About|the fictional foodstuff|the American football coach|Bob Spoo|the Luxembourgish industrialist and politician|Caspar Mathias Spoo}} [[File:Spoo Close Up 3 lite.jpg|thumb|right|Spoo close-up.]]<!--Fair use rationale: Image clearly "identifies [...] program and its contents", where the focal point of the scene is the subject of the article --> '''Spoo''' is a fictional foodstuff that served as a running joke within the ''[[Babylon 5]]'' [[science fiction]] television series. In the series' [[fictional universe]], spoo is made from worm-like creatures of the same name and is generally regarded as the most delicious food in the galaxy; the creature itself, however, is regarded with contempt by most species.<ref name=lane />{{rp|87}} Despite appearing only in a few episodes, spoo was embraced by fans and became part of the series' [[Expanded Universe|extended mythology]].<ref name=lane />{{rp|86–88}}
==Origins== Use of the word "spoo" to denote a foodstuff predates ''Babylon 5'', which began airing in 1993. The show's creator [[J. Michael Straczynski]] was a writer for the 1985 cartoon series ''[[She-Ra|She-Ra Princess of Power]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gateway to Trouble|url=http://www.he-man.org/cartoon/episode_reviews/review.php?episodeNumber=PP035|publisher=He-man.org|accessdate=2008-12-11 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080307163949/http://www.he-man.org/cartoon/episode_reviews/review.php?episodeNumber=PP035 |archivedate = March 7, 2008}}</ref> After a ''Babylon 5'' fan recalled a possible spoo reference from that show,<ref>{{cite newsgroup|author=Humble, Ed|date=1994-02-15|title=Spoo... Generation Two!|newsgroup=alt.tv.babylon-5|url=http://groups.google.com/group/alt.tv.babylon-5/browse_thread/thread/2146ff660bc1dab?hl=en&ie=UTF-8&q=straczynski+spoo+skeletor|accessdate=2008-12-11}}</ref> Straczynski replied, "Yeah, I slipped some spoo in there once. A couple of real cute (as in wanna drop a truck on them cute) elf-types offer Skeletor a bowl of Spoo."<ref name=HeMan>{{cite web|last=Straczynski|first=J. Michael|date=1994-07-07|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-8932|title=Boy, the most obscure reference...|publisher=JMSNews.com (archived from rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated)|accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref> In a 1995 interview, Straczynski referred to that scene as his favorite of the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interviews: J. Michael Straczynski|url=http://www.he-man.org/cartoon/cmotu-pop/interview-straczynski.shtml|publisher=He-man.org|accessdate=2008-12-11|year=1995 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070912112007/http://www.he-man.org/cartoon/cmotu-pop/interview-straczynski.shtml |archivedate = September 12, 2007}}</ref>
Spoo appeared in the first episode of ''Babylon 5'', where it was briefly mentioned by the [[Narn]] [[Ambassador (diplomacy)|Ambassador]], [[G'Kar]].<ref name=lane />{{rp|86–88}} Straczynski, who wrote the episode in question, was asked about spoo by fans on various internet message boards on which he frequently [[Internet marketing and fan influence on Babylon 5|participated]].<ref>Straczynski's use of internet forums is well known. See, for instance: {{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/j.-michael-straczynski/person/19536/biography.html |title= J. Michael Straczynski Biography|work=[[tv.com]]|publisher=[[CNET Networks]] |accessdate=2008-06-24}}</ref> At first, Straczynski's responses were terse: "Spoo is."<ref name=SpooIs>{{cite web|date=1994-01-27|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-13771|title=Questions for JMS (some spoile|publisher=JMSNews.com (archived from rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated)|accessdate=2008-12-07|last=Straczynski|first=J. Michael}}</ref> In another early post, he explained how he created the word: "Spoo is Oops spelled backward."<ref name=spoops>{{cite web|date=1994-08-01|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-14526|title=JMS: Spoo!?!|publisher=JMSNews.com (archived from rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5.moderated)|accessdate=2008-12-07|last=Straczynski|first=J. Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite newsgroup|author=Straczynski, J. Michael|title=JMS: Spoo!?!|url=http://groups.google.com/group/rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5/browse_thread/thread/ae1a84d207922e9b?hl=en&ie=UTF-8&q=|date=1994-08-01|accessdate=2008-12-11|newsgroup=rec.arts.sf.tv.babylon5}}</ref> He eventually noted that the taste of spoo is that of "Meat [[Gelatin dessert|Jello]]. Served chilled."<ref name=MeatJello>{{cite web|date=1996-12-18|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-6932|title=Spoo taste?|publisher=JMSNews.com (archived from [[CompuServe]])|accessdate=2008-12-07|last=Straczynski|first=J. Michael}}</ref>
After years of speculation from ''Babylon 5'' [[fandom|fans]], Straczynski finally offered an extensive explanation of the origins and nature of spoo. He said spoo are tiny, pasty, [[mealworm]]-like creatures that travel slowly in herds. Their main behavior is sighing, which "can reportedly induce unparalleled bouts of depression"<ref name=lane />{{rp|87}} in other creatures. They are raised on ranches and harvested through "whacking". Spoo are regarded with contempt by most [[Civilizations in Babylon 5|species in ''Babylon 5'']]; they "are the only creatures of which the Interstellar Animal Rights Protection League says, simply, 'Kill 'em.'"<ref name=lane />{{rp|87}} Despite this, they are "generally considered the most delicious food in all of known space".<ref name=lane />{{rp|87}}
This near-universal delight in the taste of spoo apparently doesn't include human tastes. In the episode "A View from the Gallery", neither of the two maintenance men, Mack and Bo, find spoo to their liking, despite the high price of the delicacy.
==Appearances== The ''Babylon 5'' episodes in which spoo appears or is mentioned are "[[Midnight on the Firing Line]]",<ref name=lane>{{cite book|last=Lane|first=Andy|title=The Babylon File: The Definitive, Unauthorised Guide to J. Michael Straczynski's Babylon 5|year=1997|publisher=[[Virgin Publishing]]|isbn=0-7535-0049-3}}</ref>{{rp|86–88}}<ref name=bassom>{{cite book|title=The A&ndash;Z Guide to Babylon 5|last=Bassom|first=David|publisher=[[Dell Publishing]]|year=1997|isbn=0-440-22385-7|page=208}}</ref> "[[The Geometry of Shadows]]",<ref name=lane />{{rp|185}}<ref name=bassom /><ref>{{cite web|title=Babylon 5 - "Geometry of Shadows" |url=http://www.space.com/sciencefiction/tv/babylon_5_203_001102.html |last=O'Callaghan |first=Scott |date=2000-11-02 |accessdate=2008-10-23 |publisher=[[Space.com]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207201256/http://space.com/sciencefiction/tv/babylon_5_203_001102.html |archivedate=2005-02-07 |df= }}</ref> "[[Point of No Return (Babylon 5)|Point of No Return]]",<ref name=lane />{{rp|294}} "[[And the Rock Cried Out, No Hiding Place]]", "[[A View from the Gallery]]",<ref name=lane2 />{{rp|133}} "[[A Tragedy of Telepaths]]",<ref name=lane2>{{cite book|title=The Babylon File: Volume 2|last=Lane|first=Andy|publisher=[[Virgin Publishing]]|year=1999|isbn=0-7535-0233-X}}</ref>{{rp|148}} and "[[Meditations on the Abyss]]". Spoo also appears in the "Over There" segment of the ''[[Babylon 5: The Lost Tales|Lost Tales]]'' episode "[[Babylon 5: The Lost Tales#Voices in the Dark|Voices in the Dark]]", where [[John Sheridan (Babylon 5)|President Sheridan]] at one point jokes that the product is "Spoo: The other gray meat".
Although mostly relegated to a background role, spoo was a key plot point in the season 5 episode "[[A Tragedy of Telepaths]]". The fact that Narn prefer fresh spoo while the [[Centauri (Babylon 5)|Centauri]] prefer it aged was the clue that [[G'Kar]] used to figure out that there was another Narn in the Centauri Royal Palace.<ref name=lane2 />{{rp|148}} Spoo is referenced in the Straczynski-authored [[open gaming license]]d ''[[Babylon 5 Roleplaying Game|Babylon 5: The Roleplaying Game]]''.<ref>{{cite book|first=J. Michael|last=Straczynski|authorlink=J. Michael Straczynski|first2=Matthew|last2=Sprange|authorlink2=Matthew Sprange |title=Babylon 5 The Roleplaying Game|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6TvW4b6ckVcC&dq=spoo+straczynski&pg=PT257&lpg=PT257&q=spoo#PPT236,M1|accessdate=2008-10-31|year=2006|publisher=Mongoose|isbn=1-905471-20-3|page=271}}</ref>
==Real-world references== In 1998, Boxtree UK published a ''Babylon 5'' cookbook, officially licensed from Warner Bros. Presented as if written around the year 2260, the time when most of the ''Babylon 5'' series takes place, the book contains many recipes for the various foods mentioned and seen throughout the series. Included are recipes for Narn-style spoo and Centauri-style spoo, both using currently available ingredients, with sea [[scallop]]s taking the place of spoo.<ref name=cookbook>{{cite book| title=Dining on ''Babylon 5'': Human Edition - The Ultimate Collection of Space Station Cuisine| first=Emerson| last=Briggs-Wallace|author2=Smith, Steve | isbn=0-7522-1143-9| location=UK|date=June 1998}}</ref> Straczynski claims that while dining in a restaurant prior to the 1996 [[Hugo award]] ceremony, "a fan had the waiter bring over a tray of food, christened spoo".<ref name=SpooPlate>{{cite web|last=Straczynski|first=J. Michael|date=1996-09-04|url=http://www.jmsnews.com/msg.aspx?id=1-7751|title=Small corrections... the Hugo space...|publisher=JMSNews.com (archived from [[GEnie]])|accessdate=2008-12-07}}</ref>
Spoo is [[parody|spoofed]] in the first episode of the ''[[South Park (cartoon)|South Park]]'' parody ''[[Babylon Park]]'', ''Spoohunter''.<ref name=BabylonPark>{{cite web|url=http://www.babylonpark.com/|title=Babylon Park|accessdate=2008-12-07|publisher=Infocorp Transgalactic}}</ref>
In 2008, [[Rap music|rap]]-[[filk]] artist [[Luke Ski]] recorded and released a parody of the [[Beastie Boys]] song "[[No Sleep till Brooklyn]]" called "No Sleep Till Babylon", which references spoo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefump.com/fump.php?id=1061|publisher=Funny Music Project|accessdate=2008-12-07|title=No Sleep Till Babylon|last=Ski|first=Luke|date=2008-06-10}}</ref> A stanza attributed to the ''Babylon 5'' character [[Londo Mollari]] contains the lyrics: "Spoo. All I really want is Spoo. And in the morning it's Spoo. Cause in the evening it's Spoo. I like the way that it tastes. It's blue meatballs in greyish paste..."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefump.com/lyrics.php?id=1061|publisher=Funny Music Project|accessdate=2008-12-07|title=No Sleep Till Babylon|last=Sienkowski|first=Luke Collis|date=2008-06-10}}</ref>{{Clear}}
