===English=== *{{cite book |year=1862 |author=Fedor Dostoyeffsky |title= Buried Alive: or, Ten Years Penal Servitude in Siberia |publisher=[[Longman's, Green, and Co.]] |publication-date=1881 |publication-place=London |translator-last=von Thilo |translator-first=Marie |translator-link=Marie von Thilo}} *{{cite book |year=1862 |author=Fedor Dostoïeffsky |title= The House of the Dead; or, Prison Life in Siberia |publisher= [[J.M. Dent & Sons]] |publication-place=London | publication-date=1911 |series=[[Everyman's Library]]}} *{{cite book |year=1862 |author=Fyodor Dostoevsky |title=The House of the Dead; A Novel in Two Parts |publisher=[[The Macmillan Company]] |publication-date=1915 |publication-place=New York |translator-last=Garnett |translator-first=Constance |translator-link1=Constance Garnett}} *{{cite book |year=1862 |author=Fyodor Dostoevsky |title=Notes from a Dead House |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |publication-date=2016 |isbn=978-0-307-94987-5 |translator-last1=Pevear |translator-first1=Richard |translator-link1=Richard Pevear |translator-last2=Volokhonsky |translator-first2=Larissa |translator-link2=Larissa Volokhonsky}}
==Adaptations== In 1927–1928, [[Leoš Janáček]] wrote an [[opera]]tic version of the novel, with the title ''[[From the House of the Dead]]''. It was his last opera.
In 1932, the novel was adapted to a film, directed by [[Vasili Fyodorov]] and starring [[Nikolay Khmelyov]].
