{{orphan|date = February 2009}}
In [[US Income tax|United States federal income tax]], a '''Vacation home deduction''' is a [[tax deduction]] to be claimed on an individual taxpayer's [[vacation home]].
This deduction is limited under law. Generally, a taxpayer may not deduct expenses related to a vacation home since the owner uses the property for personal enjoyment.<ref name="IRC § 280A(a).">{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/280A-|title=US CODE: Title 26,280A. Disallowance of certain expenses in connection with business use of home, rental of vacation homes, etc.|date=Sep 26, 2008|publisher=Internal Revenue Service|accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref> However, a taxpayer may claim limited deductions on a vacation home if the taxpayer uses the property as both a vacation home and [[rental property]].<ref>IRC § 280A(d).</ref>
If the taxpayer uses the property for the greater of 14 days or 10% of the number of days the property is rented, the taxpayer may deduct some of the property-related expenses.<ref>IRC § 280A(e)(1).</ref> These deductions are limited to the gross income from the rent less the general expenses attributable to the rental use of the property.<ref>IRC § 280A(c)(5).</ref> The taxpayer may deduct the expenses related to the property limited to (i) the number of days the property was rented at fair market rental value over (ii) the total number of days the property was used.<ref>IRC § 280A(e).</ref>
If the taxpayer rents the property for less than 15 days, the taxpayer may not deduct any property-related expenses.<ref>IRC § 280A(g)(1).</ref> However, in this case, the taxpayer does not have to include as income any rent attributable to the property.<ref>IRC § 280A(g)(2).</ref>
